	<text>
		<body>
			<p><persName>MORRIS NEWBURGER</persName>&#44; <lb/> PRESIDENT.</p>
			<p><persName>MAYER SULZBERGER</persName>&#44; <lb/> CHAIRMAN PUBLICATION COMMITTEE.</p>
			<p><persName>MORRIS DANNENBAUM</persName><lb/> TREASURER.</p>
			<p><persName>C. S. BERNHEIMER</persName>&#44;<lb/> ASSISTANT SECRETARY</p>
			<p rend="align(center)">The Jewish Publication Society of
				<placeName>America</placeName>. <placeName>1015 ARCH STREET&#44; P. O. BOX
					1164</placeName>&#44; <placeName>139 WEST UPSAL ST.&#44;<lb/> GERMANTOWN&#44;
					PHILADA.</placeName>
				<placeName>PHILADELPHIA</placeName>.</p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><date>June&#44; 17&#44; 1896</date>.</p>
			<p><addressee>Judge Mayer Sulzberger</addressee>&#59;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">I beg leave to send you a copy of<lb/> our correspondence with the
				contemplated English contributors<lb/> to the Bible translation&#44;m and to direct
				your attention to the<lb/> explanatory letter to <persName>Dr. Adler</persName>&#44;
				&#40;marked A&#41; which accompanied<lb/> the Instructions. The fact that this
				letter was not placed<lb/> before the gentlemen who signed the collective
				letter<lb/> of declination of <date>April 6</date>&#44; &#40;marked B&#41; can only
				be accounted<lb/> for by an oversight on the part of the secretary to <persName>Dr.
					Adler</persName>&#44; for it<lb/> was enclosed in the <sic>envelop</sic> with
				the Instructions addressed<lb/> to <persName>Dr. Adler</persName>. A second
				copy&#44; however&#44; of his letter was in the<lb/> hands of the chief Rabbi before
				the collective letter of<lb/> declination &#40;marked B&#41; was sent off as evident
				from<lb/> the P. S. to the letter &#40;marked C&#41; Whether the signers were
				in&#45;<lb/>formed of this explanatory letter&#44; I have no means of<lb/>
				ascertaining. It would seem that <persName>Mr. Joseph Jacobs</persName>&#44; at<lb/>
				the time of his writing to you upon the matter was<lb/> not aware of its existence.
				You will confer a great favor<lb/> on me if you will kindly undertake to convince
					<persName>Mr. Jacobs</persName>&#44;<lb/> that nothing was neglected on our part
				to show our English<lb/>
				<sic>brethern</sic>&#44; that our making the <persName>Leeser</persName> Bible the
				work&#45;<lb/>ing basis for our enterprise&#44; was not intended to fetter<lb/> the
				hands of the contributors in any way.</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)">Believe me&#44; dear Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)">Very Truly Yours.</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)"><persName role="author">M Jastrow</persName></p>
		</body>
